Black bean bundle dye 🫘✨ If you’re like me & your pantry or fridge have a few older food items knocking around 〰 you might like to try making color before you toss expired produce or dry goods. 
Wilted red cabbage? Expired black rice? Black bean soaking water? There are many other ideas listed this month in ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨ too for food waste dyes!
I’m dyeing this playsilk to give as a gift for my youngest daughter this Christmas 🎁 Playsilks are fantastically simple open ended toys that can become so many things! Capes, dancing ribbons, braided into hair, clipped up to make fort walls, babydoll carriers, wrapping for gifts, etc. The possibilities are limitless- one of my favorite resources for playsilks ideas is @sarahssilks 💫
And Bundle Dyeing is a fun, simple and kid friendly activity whose results are always unique & one-of-a-kind! If you’re interested in learning about all of my favorite plants that can make beautiful colors & marks on cloth- my ✨Bundle Dyeing + EcoPrinting✨ online video workshop is for you! I cover multiple methods for pretreatments of fabric to ensure the dye stays bound to the fabric including my preferred ✨mordant method✨ that contributes to the maximum saturated color & texture on the fabric. And the workshop comes with a reference sheet with images & listings of which dyes make what colors on both plant & protein fibers 📝
My Workshops make great gifts themselves & gift certificates for any of my 5 workshops are on sale in my webshop until the end of the year 🙌🏻

Your natural dyeing practice can be whatever you want it to be- centered around accessible plants, inclusive of your youngest family members, calculated and researched for the most durable lasting color possible. It’s up to you! 
I’ve designed my workshops & ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨ to be as transparent as possible about all the options- encouraging of whatever your aim might be because it’s your practice & should hopefully fill YOU with joy. 
Happy color making!

Avocado dyed 🥑wool slippers 🐑 
This season I’m treating myself with the gift of naturally tinted, cozy feet care of my incredible friends at @kyrgies 🐑

The felted wool behaved wonderfully in the dyebath & the slippers kept their perfect molded shaped through multiple baths of mordant, dye, rinsing & washing. I am thoroughly impressed with the quality of these house shoes. 💗

The avocado pit dyebath used to dye these shoes was made using my preferred extraction procedure- its covered in specific detail in my food waste themed ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨ join to make your food waste dye dreams come true 🥑

Printing ✨Holly✨ Ribbon with local plants 🌿🎁 
Toyon or ‘Heteromeles arbitufolia’ - native word ‘Ashuwet’ - is one of my local & abundant plants with bright showy red winter berries & leaves possessing excellent dye properties. It’s the official native plant of Los Angeles, an incredibly important medicine & edible plant for local indigenous people & is even the namesake for ‘Hollywood’. 

I don’t have a local source for holly plants here & wanted to create some special ribbon for gift wrapping this year when I realized that I could transform what what locally available to achieve the look I was hoping for. Cutting the holly shape from the leaves was simple & relaxing…

✂️AND this custom shape cutting technique could be employed for so many different leaves- no matter where you reside, there’s surely a plant whose leaf could be fashioned to your artistic intention.

Magic color changing Candy Cane Paper chains with Natural Rhubarb Root paint 🪄🤍❤️
Rhubarb root is an incredible natural dye 〰 The roots contain special dye compounds whose tones can magically shift dramatically from one color family to the next. This simple activity requires no mordant or fixative as Rhubarb root is full of tannins & it’s dye compound classification allows it to effectively tint textiles & paper without necessarily needing a fixative. 

Here I’m using dried Desert Rhubarb roots grown by my friends at @grandprismaticseed - native to the southwest desert bioregion- also know as Canaigre (‘sourcane’), or Tanners Dock because if the incredibly high content of tannin contained in its roots. The tannins & unique dye compounds that contribute to its durability as a dye also allow for this magical color change 💛〰❤️ 
AND this technique can work with almost any other variety of rhubarb root & many other closely related plants- see a full list in ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨.
Rhubarb root has strong medicinal properties & can commonly be found from herbal suppliers as well as dye suppliers if you’re not growing any yourself- I also have a list of resources included in ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨ 

AND if you’d like to grow your own (as I’m definitely planning on including in my garden again next year) @grandprismaticseed has seed for this variety 🤎
I was very impressed with the amount of dye held within these roots as this was the second round of extraction - I’ll be sharing the colors & project from the first extraction soon.

This activity was perfect to share with my children including discussions on art & science as they witness the color shift happen. Join me this season in reveling in the magic of plants! 🌲🪄

Dyeing with Christmas Tree Trimmings🌲A plentiful, accessible & very effective natural dye source is easy to find this time of year 🌲🎄🌲 after you’ve finished enjoying your tree- consider making use of branches & needles to make dye 💛🤎🖤
More than 20 million trees are harvested each year to bring into homes for the holiday season- presenting much opportunity for additional use for this plant source before being chipped and composted. Even just a few bough trimmings will go a long way in the dye pot either as a tannin pre-treatment for dyes or as dye on its own! AND this dye comes with a bonus Pine aroma that fills the air with a fresh wintery scent.
I kept this organic cotton pine dyed set from @mirablackman simple with no pre-fixative process- focusing on the tannin content of the dyebath to color this locally made top & leggings. With no pre-mordant process to fuss with I had more time to focus on creating 2 extraction pots- one from my Christmas Tree -A Noble Fir & one from my local Ponderosa Pine tree. 
The unique tannin compounds present in my local Pine & Christmas tree become apparent especially when they dramatically shift in tone & saturation after a bath in my home made iron solution. 🪄🖤
My local pine created a warmer green leaning grey while my Christmas tree dyed leggings resulted in a lovely complex purple toned grey.
Looking forward to relaxing a bit this winter break in my Pine dyed- waste tapping ensemble.

If you’d like to learn more- I’m sharing all about the diverse family of Pine •Pinaceae•  trees including many conifers that contain an abundance of tannin & flavonoid dyes in ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨ & my Solid Foundations & Extracting Color Workshops cover Tannins & Dyes extensively.

New Tutorial ✨Natural Dyeing Wood✨ this month I’m sharing how to create natural color on wood 🌈 🪵 I’ve loved wearing my naturally dyed beads over the past few years as a year-round constant plant power reminder of my garden. 

Naturally dyeing wood beads is a wonderful entrance point to dyeing wood- the dye baths can be small and the process requires relatively little plant matter to make tiny yet hugely satisfying results. 💎🌈

Wood beads can be used to make jewelry, crafts, decor, gifts, and can become fun tools for beading, stringing, counting & art activities with children.

The tutorial in ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨ covers the entire process including a flexible method of naturally pre-treating -or- •mordanting• and step by step detailed instructions for dyeing & finishing wood for good color saturation & durability over time.

Pine Cone Dye ✨🌲💗 this ponderosa pine cone dye bath created the perfect pink hue to color a lingerie set from my friend @saviadeoro 🎀 I’ve been holding onto this silk set from Savia de Oro for years waiting for the right dye to strike the pot ~ this sweet pink color is a local tone that is a real treat for the winter dyer 🌲💗

Pine cones can be used at various stages of development for the dyepot & will give different colors depending on the seasonal tannin content & dyeing procedure such as water type or quality & extraction time.
I followed a dye procedure I like to use with other ✨condensed tannnin✨ rich dyestuffs (like avocado pits) to coax a pink tone from my local pine cones - the exact procedure is covered in ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨ if you’d like to learn how.

I pre-treated the silk bralette & culottes with a unique method of effective mordanting that I typically reserve for textiles that I plan to plant print which resulted in a lovely rich dye color. I teach this method of pretreatment in my ✨Bundle Dyeing & EcoPrinting✨ online workshop if you’d like to learn a very effective way to mordant that is water wise & results in fantastic colors & plant prints.

My ✨Solid Foundations✨ & ✨Extracting Color + Dyeing Fiber✨ online workshops will walk you through the multitude of ways to create lasting & vibrant natural dye colors from sustainably grown & sourced plants traditionally used for dye & the plants you have around you!

The combination of plant derived blue (🌿indigo + woad🌿) & certain types of porous clays creates a spectacularly stable color that can withstand the degradation factors that all plant based dyes & pigments must tolerate as they travel through time on earth. 

This method of making a hardy blue clay compound can employ any indigo or woad extract (even homegrown!) and will feel 🪄miraculous🪄as it makes use of the tiniest amounts of blue pigment stretching the color payoff to the max. A little bit of precious plant blue color really can go a long long way! And the resulting color range possible: from sky to cerulean, turquoise & teal is sublime ☁️🦋

Application use is full of possibility including many different types of paint for wood, ceramics, handmade paper & murals. Here I’m making watercolor & oil paints with which I painted a wood frame for my beloved @sophiaghaas natural color garden collage 🌼🎨🖼️

This technique is often referred to as •Maya Blue• because of archaeological focus on ancient murals & objects in central Mexico where it had been employed for centuries. Much gratitude goes to @tintoreriamexicana & @seaspellfiber & @michel.garcia84 from whom I’ve learned history, chemistry & the diverse cultural provenance & significance rooted with this color.

I have a small precious caché of Pernambuco shavings that I have guarded and used sparingly for the past 8 years gifted to me from a friend who carves violin bows- one of the last allowed uses for this tree due to the management efforts of the violin bow industry. Because of the history of over exploitation, Brazilwood (Pernambuco- Caesalpinia echinata specifically- the botanical cousin to Sappanwood) is now a rarity in dyers’ cupboards. 
The shavings come from the bow carving process are in the perfect condition for ideal dye extraction & application. This is just one tiny example of the immense potential for creative natural color application that exists when byproducts of human consumption industries (agricultural, construction, etc.) can be tapped & intertwined, where clever waste intervention can become opportunity. Natural hair dye with local wild Cochineal💓
The cacti down the street from our home are bristling with wild cochineal ‘Dactylopius opuntiae’ 🌵
A small amount collected was perfect for a fun & simple natural hair dye for my pink loving gal. Soon we’ll add some blue with our annual indigo hair dyeing session too! 🧜🏽‍♀️

❣️Cochineal is one of the oldest colorants used in the Americas, dating back to the second century BC. A parasitic scale insect that makes its home on the host plant of many types of Opuntia Cacti. The colors achieved can be brilliant pinks, reds, purples and maroons and a little bit of dyestuff goes a long way. The carmine -or- carminic acid (a natural deterrent to other threatening insects) contained accounts for the color, and is often used by the cosmetics and food industry as a colorant when extracted from cultivated varieties of Dactylopius (‘Coccus’ Species). 

📌Cochineal has been cultivated for centuries by native guardians in central Mexico and Peru and has been highly valued for its light and washfast coloring ability & versatility of shade depending on preparation and water quality in extraction.

Local Cochineal pink hair dye🎀
This is how we did it:
*This method could be used with wild or cultivated cochineal, or even cochineal extract. 
1. collect cochineal - *cochineal is a parasitic insect that lives on opuntia cacti* it’s not a vegan dye & a personal choice to employ it as a dye as is the choice to ingest/use food/cosmetics tinted with ‘Carmine red’ - I respect anyone’s choice to avoid this dye. 
2. add water & make a strong extract from the cochineal- wild cochineal contains less color than cultivated cochineal but still has a good deal of ❣️carminic acid❣️ (the precious red color) to give
3. strain & add a squeeze of lemon (optional - this aids in the dye bond with hair)
4. add a small amount of dissolved alum (alum sulfate). We used about 1/8 teaspoon. This is also optional & also aids in the dye binding to hair. You can find alum in spice sections of grocery or with pickling supplies. @botanicalcolors also sells alum & cochineal.
5. add a pinch of natural thickener like guar gum to make the dye more paint like in consistency & easier to paint on without making a mess
6. paint on hair with foil & let it sit on the hair for an hour or two if you can. You can also heat the foils with a hair dryer to aid the dye in binding even more
7. rinse, wash & enjoy naturally dyed hair 🎀

I’ve saved our rinse water to make pigment- this process is covered in full in my ✨Pigment Tutorial✨ in my online Shop.

⏰ You may also like to apply the leaves, massage for just a few minutes then use a piece of aluminum foil to keep the leaves directly on the hair & let it sit for another 15 minutes for extra deep color. 

💦 After massaging in hair for 15 minutes, rinse, untangle the remaining leaves, wash & marvel at the natural blue hued locks! 

🧼 The color lasts for weeks through normal washing & wear & throughout the growing season we will reapply indigo a few times for a teal aqua color recharge 🌿🌞

👉🏼This whole process is covered in step by step detail in ✨A Year in Natural Dyes✨ & is available bro download & keep forever to anyone who joins before August 31.
